ome other very well-defined area, such as in the middle of a block of buildings.  You could have passageways mid-block leading to the park space. (Although one would have to be careful with the design in order to maximize visibility.)  In any event, park space should be designed as a \"room\" with \"walls.\"  Buildings shouldn\'t have \"front yards.\"<br /><br />* It would have been best to create a master plan and then divvy up the work on different parts of the plan to different architects.  Large complexes designed by single architects are aesthetically very risky.  I would encourage a site that will appear to blend into the streetscape and not appear to be a separate complex all its own.',0,'1','','',0,0),(4,491,'NikoV','noreply@blogger.com','http://www.blogger.com/profile/13260084966546691074','','2011-11-27 09:38:28','2011-11-27 09:38:28','I think your critique of the plan is valid, and different architects for the entire site would\'ve definitely been preferred, but the size of the plan negates the \'towers in the park\' aspect to a degree. <br /><br />Many of the failures of \'tower in park\' developments come--IMO--from the lack of overall density. You can have five 20-story towers over 4 acres, but that isn\'t terribly dense, and it\'s made worse by the open space.<br /><br />The scale of Hudson Yards is what will hopefully differentiate it from such developments. It will be very difficult for the area to be deserted when it will contain dozens of 50+ story buildings. I definitely agree that skyscraper \'front yards\' are undesirable, but the Hudson Yards plan calls for a boulevard running from (roughly) ten blocks, from 30th on north, that should be the backbone of the area. <br /><br />I really wish the site would have been broken up with streets, though. One of the greatest travesties in NYC is anything that deviates from the original grid, and it should be restored in full--including other sites in town, particularly the public housing developments (Stuy Town, etc).',0,'1','','',0,0),(5,425,'dannysganymedestuff','noreply@blogger.com','http://www.blogger.com/profile/05578223271534500091','','2012-04-13 05:01:46','2012-04-13 05:01:46','Lol the Displeased Union rat.<br />Great pics though, I\'m looking forward to how this ends up to look like.',0,'1','','',0,0),(6,417,'Andrew Fine','noreply@blogger.com','http://www.blogger.com/profile/11410776900972800733','','2012-04-18 13:14:41','2012-04-18 13:14:41','Yimby- Looks like great minds think alike! Impressive pics, especially from distance, this is a monster. On a side note, can I ask you what gadget you are using for your social media sharing at the bottom of your posts. I am trying to dislodge an inactive twitter share and google buzz gadget and yours looks like the best out there.',0,'1','','',0,0),(7,417,'NikoV','noreply@blogger.com','http://www.blogger.com/profile/13260084966546691074','','2012-04-18 18:47:03','2012-04-18 18:47:03','I just use whatever default gadget comes with the blogger layout, not sure exactly what that is? I was actually looking for the one that floats alongside the posts as you scroll, and couldn\'t find it!<br /><br />One57 is definitely enormous, although I can\'t wait till they finally take the blue wrapping off the cladding in front... the silver is going to look fantastic. The dynamic between this and neighboring projects (both 225 W57th and 220 CPS should be getting off the ground soon) will definitely push the neighborhood much more upscale.',0,'1','','',0,0),(8,417,'Andrew Fine','noreply@blogger.com','http://www.blogger.com/profile/11410776900972800733','','2012-04-20 17:20:29','2012-04-20 17:20:29','That 220 is a never ending story! Hope they do a tasteful job. <br /><br />I found a floater, but it would only post the blog, not a specific posting.<br /><br />Keep up the good work. I\'ll throw you on my blog roll when I get the chance.',0,'1','','',0,0),(9,411,'WhatHouse.co.uk','noreply@blogger.com','http://www.blogger.com/profile/16